05/12/2006
BRUSSELS, Belgium -- EU security chief Javier Solana said in Brussels on Monday (December 4th) that the EU would discuss the possibility of re-launching Stabilisation and Association Agreement talks with Serbia after next month's parliamentary elections.
During a joint news conference with NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop Scheffer, Solana added that the level of Belgrade's co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal would continue to be the major determining factor.
Both Solana and de Hoop Scheffer praised NATO's recent decision to invite Serbia, BiH and Montenegro into the Partnership for Peace programme.
In other news Monday, Montenegro, Serbia and Italy signed a trilateral agreement on reprogramming the former federal union's debt to the Paris Club of creditors.
The document was sealed on the sidelines of Italian Deputy Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema's official visit to Belgrade.
(Danas - 05/12/06;
Beta, Tanjug, RTS - 04/12/06)
